    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div type="letter">
                <div type="text">
                    <opener>
                        <placeName><hi rend="italic">Down.</hi> | Beckenham | <hi rend="italic">Kent. S.E.</hi></placeName>
                        <date>Ap. 8 1871</date>
                        <salute>Madam</salute>
                    </opener>
                    <div type="transcription">
                        <p>I have the honour to acknowledge, on the part of Mrs Darwin &amp; myself, the request that we should agree to our names being added to the General Committee for securing medical education to women.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
                        <p>I shall be very glad to have my name put down, <hi rend="underline">or</hi> that of Mrs Darwin but I should not like both our names to appear.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
                        <p>With sincere good wishes for the cause you are so generously aiding I beg leave to remain | Madam | your obedient servant | Charles Darwin</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                
            </div>
            
            
            <div type="footnotes">
                <note xml:id="foot.f1">Stevenson’s letter to CD has not been found. Stevenson was an honorary secretary of the Committee for Securing a Medical Education to the Women of Edinburgh, which was formed in support of <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_8995.xml">Sophia Jex-Blake</ref> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5933.xml"><hi rend="italic">ODNB</hi></ref> s.v. Stevenson, Louisa; <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_9871.xml">Roberts 1993</ref>, pp. 97–100).</note>
                <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD’s name appeared on the committee (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_9871.xml">Roberts 1993</ref>, p. 97).</note>
                </div>
        
